\begin_layout Section
Materials and Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section,
 a detailed presentation of the datasets used as well as the machine learning techniques used in the experiments performed will be provided.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The dataset employed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the purposes of our study,
 we combined two distinct data sources.
 On the one hand,
 to analyze the climatological conditions,
 we employed Historical Weather Data from Visual Crossing 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.visualcrossing.com/ 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Visual crossing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (last accessed on 02 February 2026),
 which compiles information from a range of authoritative sources,
 including national meteorological agencies,
 global climate datasets,
 and satellite observations.
 Access to the historical dataset required completing the registration process,
 after which we selected the data -access interface,
 specified the region of interest,
 and defined the temporal range.
 Data retrieval was then carried out under the free access tier,
 which allows up to 1,000 records per day.
 The procedure is generally straightforward,
 with the only notable constraint being the daily limit of 1,000 data points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand,
 for the analysis of forest / wild fires,
 we relied on the open data provided by the Hellenic Fire Service 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.fireservice.gr/el_GR/synola-dedomenon
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ( last accessed on 02 February 2026).
 The fire data are collected and updated each year by the individual fire stations responsible for reporting incidents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The dataset description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this study,
 we obtained historical meteorological data for the period 2000 – 2024,
 providing a roughly 25 year record to support our fire duration according to climate patterns analysis.
 We additionally selected regions across different latitudes and longitudes,
 in Greece,
 to achieve a more comprehensive representation of the study areas.
 The selected regions of interest are:
 Attica,
 Eastern Macedonia and Thrace,
 and Crete 
