\begin_layout Standard
To evaluate the proposed wildfire danger assessment method,
 a 10\SpecialChar nobreakdash
fold cross\SpecialChar nobreakdash
validation procedure was applied using the WEKA environment.
 WEKA was developed at the University of Waikato in New Zealand,
 and its name derives from Waikato Environment for Knowledge Analysis.
 It offers a wide range of machine learning algorithms that can be readily applied to any dataset.
 In addition,
 it provides numerous tools for dataset transformation,
 including methods for discretization and sampling.
 Users can preprocess their data,
 apply a learning algorithm,
 and subsequently examine both the resulting classifier and its performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WEKA 2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 WEKA has been used in numerous research studies,
 such as:
 model construction and accuracy evaluation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Attwal 2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Heart Disease Prediction Systems
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Saleh 2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Predicting the Duration of Forest Fires
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kopitsa 2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and many others.
 In this experiment the CSV dataset was imported,
 in WEKA tool and the target variable was set to the Final_DangerClass_combination attribute.
 Various machine learning models were trained and tested across 10 automatically generated train/test splits.
 The results demonstrated that the model Multilayer Perceptron (MLP) classifier achieved 100% accuracy in predicting the final danger class (1),
 indicating that the newly developed fire danger rule is fully identifiable and predictable based on the combined climatological and operational fire incident data.
 In addition,
 the Random Forest algorithm achieved the second best performance for all the datasets:
 Attica 
